#IMPORTING LIBRARIES AND DATA PREPROCESSING

import tensorflow as tf
from tensorflow.keras import datasets, layers, models
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

##Dataset and data loader code from tutorial website:
##Source [1]: https://www.tensorflow.org/tutorials/images/cnn?fbclid=IwAR2N3-3QOzwejFV-Bj0jpULwzI4M3GHBzNcy3HhkmTbXM7rSmLNPa-weYKY

(train_images, train_labels), (test_images, test_labels) = datasets.cifar10.load_data()

# Normalize pixel values to be between 0 and 1
train_images, test_images = train_images / 255.0, test_images / 255.0

class_names = ['airplane', 'automobile', 'bird', 'cat', 'deer',
               'dog', 'frog', 'horse', 'ship', 'truck']

##End of source [1]
In [15]:
#MODEL 1 WITHOUT OVERFITTING MEASURES

##Model inspried by the AlexNet architecture, but heavily simplified to reduce training time drastically, and reduce overfitting

model1 = models.Sequential()
#First Conv section
model1.add(layers.Conv2D(96, (3,3), padding='same' , activation='relu', input_shape=(32, 32, 3)))

#Second Conv section
model1.add(layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2)))
model1.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
model1.add(layers.Conv2D(128, (3,3), padding='same', activation='relu'))

#Third Conv section
model1.add(layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2)))
model1.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
model1.add(layers.Conv2D(128, (3, 3), padding='same', activation='relu'))
model1.add(layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), padding='same', activation='relu'))
model1.add(layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), padding='same', activation='relu'))
model1.add(layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2)))
model1.add(layers.BatchNormalization())

#Fully connected layers section
model1.add(layers.Flatten())
model1.add(layers.Dense(128, activation='relu'))
model1.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
model1.add(layers.Dense(256, activation='relu'))
model1.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
model1.add(layers.Dense(10))
In [16]:
##Also from source [1]:
#https://www.tensorflow.org/tutorials/images/cnn?fbclid=IwAR2N3-3QOzwejFV-Bj0jpULwzI4M3GHBzNcy3HhkmTbXM7rSmLNPa-weYKY

#Compiling of model
model1.compile(optimizer='adam',
            loss=tf.keras.losses.SparseCategoricalCrossentropy(from_logits=True),
            metrics=['acc'])

#Training of first model
history1 = model1.fit(train_images, train_labels, epochs=10, 
            validation_data=(test_images, test_labels))
              
#plotting two graphs, one to show accuracy and one for loss
plt.plot(history1.history['acc'], label='accuracy')
plt.plot(history1.history['val_acc'], label = 'val_accuracy')
plt.title('Model Accuracy')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
plt.legend(loc='lower right')
plt.show()

plt.plot(history1.history['loss'], label='loss')
plt.plot(history1.history['val_loss'], label = 'val_loss')
plt.title('Model Loss')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.ylabel('Loss')
plt.legend(loc='lower right')
plt.show()

#Final evaluation of the model just to get an official final value of accuracy
test_loss, test_acc = model1.evaluate(test_images,  test_labels, verbose=2)

print("Accuracy of ", test_acc * 100, "%")

##end of source [1]

##FIRST MODEL WITH OVERFITTING MEASURES ADDED

model2 = models.Sequential()
#First Conv section
model2.add(layers.Conv2D(96, (3,3), padding='same' , activation='relu', input_shape=(32, 32, 3)))

#Second Conv section
model2.add(layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2)))
model2.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
model2.add(layers.Conv2D(128, (3,3), padding='same', activation='relu'))

#Third Conv section
model2.add(layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2)))
model2.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
model2.add(layers.Conv2D(128, (3, 3), padding='same', activation='relu'))
model2.add(layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), padding='same', activation='relu'))
model2.add(layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), padding='same', activation='relu'))
model2.add(layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2)))
model2.add(layers.BatchNormalization())

#Fully connected layers section with dropout layers to reduce overfitting
model2.add(layers.Flatten())
model2.add(layers.Dense(128, activation='relu'))
model2.add(layers.Dropout(0.4))
model2.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
model2.add(layers.Dense(256, activation='relu'))
model2.add(layers.Dropout(0.4))
model2.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
model2.add(layers.Dense(10))

#COMPILING, TRAINING AND TESTING THE MODEL

##Learning rate scheduler and custom optimizer from source [2]:
##https://towardsdatascience.com/dont-overfit-how-to-prevent-overfitting-in-your-deep-learning-models-63274e552323

#Fine tuning of schedule parameters to reach better accuracy
lr_schedule = tf.keras.optimizers.schedules.ExponentialDecay(
    initial_learning_rate=0.001,
    decay_steps=10000,
    decay_rate=0.99)

opt = tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=lr_schedule)

## end of source [2]

##Also from source [1]:
#https://www.tensorflow.org/tutorials/images/cnn?fbclid=IwAR2N3-3QOzwejFV-Bj0jpULwzI4M3GHBzNcy3HhkmTbXM7rSmLNPa-weYKY

#Compiling of model
model2.compile(optimizer=opt,
            loss=tf.keras.losses.SparseCategoricalCrossentropy(from_logits=True),
            metrics=['acc'])

#Training of first model
history2 = model2.fit(train_images, train_labels, epochs=10, 
            validation_data=(test_images, test_labels))
              
#plotting two graphs, one to show accuracy and one for loss
plt.plot(history1.history['val_acc'], label='Model 1 val_accuracy')
plt.plot(history1.history['acc'], label='Model 1 accuracy')
plt.plot(history2.history['val_acc'], label = 'Model 1 Overfit val_accuracy')
plt.plot(history2.history['acc'], label='Model 1 Overfit accuracy')
plt.title('Model Accuracy')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
plt.legend(loc='lower right')
plt.show()

plt.plot(history1.history['val_loss'], label='Model 1 (no overfit measures) val_loss')
plt.plot(history2.history['val_loss'], label='Model 1 (with overfit measures) val_loss')
plt.title('Model Loss')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.ylabel('Loss')
plt.legend(loc='lower right')
plt.show()

#Final evaluation of the model just to get an official final value of accuracy
test_loss, test_acc = model2.evaluate(test_images,  test_labels, verbose=2)

print("Accuracy of ", test_acc * 100, "%")

#BUILDING THE SECOND MODEL

##Extremely simple architecture with only two conv layers and one fully connected layer
##MaxPooling, batch normalization and dropout layers were added to slightly increase accuracy above 70%

model5 = models.Sequential()

#First Conv section
model5.add(layers.Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', input_shape=(32, 32, 3)))
model5.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
model5.add(layers.BatchNormalization())

#Second Conv section
model5.add(layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu'))
model5.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
model5.add(layers.BatchNormalization())

#Single fully connected layer with dropout layer to reduce overfitting.
model5.add(layers.Flatten())
model5.add(layers.Dense(64, activation='relu'))
model5.add(layers.Dropout(0.3))

#Final fully connected layer to classify the images
model5.add(layers.Dense(10))
In [36]:
#COMPILING, TRAINING AND TESTING THE SECOND MODEL

            loss=tf.keras.losses.SparseCategoricalCrossentropy(from_logits=True),
            metrics=['acc'])

history5 = model5.fit(train_images, train_labels, epochs=10, 
            validation_data=(test_images, test_labels))
